 It's pretty powerful and lightweight.

29
00:04:56,360 --> 00:05:02,670
 Codex App, which is really good for just direct use in Windows and Mac.

30
00:05:02,670 --> 00:05:07,310
 And then inside your IDE for a more integrated workflow

31
00:05:07,310 --> 00:05:11,410
 with your files, so you can directly edit things while you're going.

32
00:05:11,410 --> 00:05:15,130
 Here's just basically how to set it up.

33
00:05:15,130 --> 00:05:19,630
 There is the link and the install for the CLI.

34
00:05:19,630 --> 00:05:24,580
 You get it if you're in VS Code, just from the plugin section by searching Codex.

35
00:05:24,580 --> 00:05:32,820
 So to start, you want to open a repository.

36
00:05:32,820 --> 00:05:35,910
 You can also do it without one, just folderless.

37
00:05:35,910 --> 00:05:47,650
 But basically, it needs a folder to think about and to put files into, test them from, and so on and so forth.

38
00:05:47,650 --> 00:05:50,120
 I'll show you the agents one as an example.

39
00:05:50,120 --> 00:05:52,120
 This agents.md file is pretty important.

40
00:05:52,120 --> 00:05:58,600
 It is the, essentially, set of rules and instructions that you give the agents who knows how to update your codebase,

41
00:05:58,600 --> 00:06:00,990
 run your code, things like that.

42
00:06:00,990 --> 00:06:05,050
 You can also ask it to update these files with you as you go.

43
00:06:05,050 --> 00:06:09,270
 I essentially use it as a map to point it at the most important parts.

44
00:06:09,270 --> 00:06:13,600
 You just start with the prompt.

45
00:06:13,600 --> 00:06:19,360
 If you're not sure what you want it to do yet, I like to keep a to-do list and ask it, you know,

46
00:06:19,360 --> 00:06:21,360
 "What's new on the to-do list? What's something you can do yourself?

47
00:06:21,360 --> 00:06:25,680
 What's something that you think would be high value that you need me to check over?"

48
00:06:25,680 --> 00:06:26,740
 Stuff like that.

49
00:06:26,740 --> 00:06:30,980
 And so let's talk about the agents.

50
00:06:30,980 --> 00:06:35,570
 So it starts with a prompt, same as normal ChatGPT would.

51
00:06:35,570 --> 00:06:38,110
 And then it does the inference.

52
00:06:38,110 --> 00:06:44,540
 And it also runs tool calls, essentially just small snippets of code on your computer.

53
00:06:44,540 --> 00:06:49,520
 And it keeps doing that until it is satisfied and then it will respond to you.

54
00:06:49,520 --> 00:06:52,480
 At this point, it's often just the tool calls.

55
00:06:52,480 --> 00:06:54,480
 The response is not actually what you're looking for.

56
00:06:54,480 --> 00:06:55,480
 You're looking for the actions that it takes.

57
00:06:55,480 --> 00:07:00,270
 One thing to keep in mind is context.

58
00:07:00,270 --> 00:07:05,930
 When you run the prompt, ChatGPT will look at all of the information that it's fed.

59
00:07:05,930 --> 00:07:13,690
 So that would mean the agents.md as a start and anything it chooses to read, plus the prompt.

60
00:07:13,690 --> 00:07:26,200
 So yeah, it can hold a lot of text, like four to six hundred pages.

61
00:07:26,200 --> 00:07:30,580
 But some of these repositories and long workflows get a lot longer.

62
00:07:30,580 --> 00:07:37,880
 What it does now is compact the context after a while, which means basically writing a summary for itself.

63
00:07:37,880 --> 00:07:48,000
 It's very important to think about what you put in the context window because that is directly influencing the model's output from start to finish.

64
00:07:48,000 --> 00:08:41,600
 Sorry guys.

65
00:08:41,600 --> 00:10:02,500
 So Codex does manage the context.

66
00:10:02,500 --> 00:10:11,200
 Like I said, long conversations will lead to a bit of context drop where it gets confused and forgets things.

67
00:10:11,200 --> 00:10:17,510
 It does do its best here, but you do want to try to start a new conversation when you find things are going off the rails.

68
00:10:17,510 --> 00:10:19,890
 You can rely on this context window.

69
00:10:19,890 --> 00:10:26,890
 The context is automatically compacted, but only to a certain extent.

70
00:10:26,890 --> 00:10:32,890
 So yeah, when you work with Codex, you want to make sure that you're delegating, but you don't want to totally remove yourself from the process.

71
00:10:32,890 --> 00:10:41,120
 You need to make sure that you're learning and actually thinking about what you want and what makes a successful app, product, or whatever you're working on.

72
00:10:41,120 --> 00:10:48,260
 So yeah, start by building the perfect context, not the perfect prompt.

73
00:10:48,260 --> 00:10:50,260
 Remember, the prompt is just part of the context.

74
00:10:50,260 --> 00:10:53,710
 It's going to go through and it's going to search your codebase.

75
00:10:53,710 --> 00:10:56,930
 It might search external sources, things like that.

76
00:10:56,930 --> 00:11:00,950
 You want to make sure it's getting high quality information at every step.

77
00:11:00,950 --> 00:11:02,950
 Faster validation means better outcomes.

78
00:11:02,950 --> 00:11:08,160
 That means just checking stuff, getting a test signal itself, things like that.

79
00:11:08,160 --> 00:11:10,160
 Use the agent to learn, not vibe code.

80
00:11:10,160 --> 00:11:16,780
 If you're vibe coding, you want to make sure you're actually engaging with the process at every step.

81
00:11:16,780 --> 00:11:22,360
 So start with the goal.

82
00:11:22,360 --> 00:11:23,360
 Choose the files you want.

83
00:11:23,360 --> 00:11:25,360
 Like I said, you can bake these into your repo.

84
00:11:25,360 --> 00:11:27,290
 Strengths.

85
00:11:27,290 --> 00:11:29,440
 Tell it not to do certain things if you need.

86
00:11:29,440 --> 00:11:34,790
 And then give it an actual goal, because otherwise it'll just keep running forever and not really know what it's doing.

87
00:11:34,790 --> 00:11:39,040
 And it might decide it's finished before you want it to be.

88
00:11:39,040 --> 00:11:41,790
 And you can use plan mode.

89
00:11:41,790 --> 00:11:44,770
 You can get into that with shift app or slash plan.

90
00:11:44,770 --> 00:11:54,480
 And this will basically have it walk through a series of questions about your prompt in order to build a longer prompt for itself that you can review before you execute.

91
00:11:54,480 --> 00:11:59,270
 This is super useful, especially when I'm not sure what I want to do quite yet.

92
00:11:59,270 --> 00:12:08,290
 I have like a starter idea, but the details aren't quite filled in and they are still sensitive to, yeah, exactly what's running.

93
00:12:08,290 --> 00:12:12,040
 Use cases.

94
00:12:12,040 --> 00:12:15,010
 The learning of code base.

95
00:12:15,010 --> 00:12:18,430
 Especially helpful when learning about somebody else's code.

96
00:12:18,430 --> 00:12:23,730
 If you guys have been reading code a lot, it's one thing to read back your own code.

97
00:12:23,730 --> 00:12:26,690
 But reading somebody else's code can be a bit of an adventure.

98
00:12:26,690 --> 00:12:30,180
 This can help with that a lot.

99
00:12:30,180 --> 00:12:33,490
 Building plans like we just discussed.

100
00:12:33,490 --> 00:12:36,490
 Investigating changes instead of just going right ahead and implementing them.

101
00:12:36,490 --> 00:12:40,280
 And then taking in error logs and determining re-causes.

102
00:12:40,280 --> 00:12:42,530
 This is a really big one for me.

103
00:12:42,530 --> 00:12:49,350
 Making sure my apps are outputting information on what has happened so that I can go in and instead of having to guess,

104
00:12:49,350 --> 00:12:54,460
 call Codex, look at what happened, diagnose the error and suggest a fix.

105
00:12:54,460 --> 00:12:57,710
 It saves a lot of time for me and makes things a lot higher quality.

106
00:12:57,710 --> 00:13:03,540
 Review, which success, I believe that's as a skill.

107
00:13:03,540 --> 00:13:05,890
 Same with plans.

108
00:13:05,890 --> 00:13:12,590
 Something that I would do pretty regularly to make sure that your code is up to date and high quality as you keep moving forward.

109
00:13:12,590 --> 00:13:25,180
 And write documentation, which again is helpful for not just agents, but for users themselves and for yourself so they remember what you've been doing.

110
00:13:25,180 --> 00:13:29,030
 Writing tests with Codex.

111
00:13:29,030 --> 00:13:32,450
 I will say you might not want to write all of your tests with Codex.

112
00:13:32,450 --> 00:13:35,590
 It will sometimes write tests that are a little too easy to pass.

113
00:13:35,590 --> 00:13:42,770
 But it is very good at writing unit tests and to be honest, having simple tests is a lot better than having none.

114
00:13:42,770 --> 00:13:48,750
 You do want to review these to make sure they're achieving the actual goals you want.

115
00:13:48,750 --> 00:13:58,140
 But as you make changes, if you don't have a set of tests, there is no way of knowing if you've broken something while updating.

116
00:13:58,140 --> 00:14:00,590
 Which is going to happen a lot.

117
00:14:00,590 --> 00:14:06,540
 Using unit tests also helps with collaborating and like I said, remember to review it yourself.

118
00:14:06,540 --> 00:14:11,500
 So that it's a test you actually want to verify repeatedly.

119
00:14:11,500 --> 00:14:18,760
 And not just something that is because it is important.

120
00:14:18,760 --> 00:14:22,130
 It's essentially more about tests.

121
00:14:22,130 --> 00:14:36,000
 Again, the faster you're able to iterate on the step of the loop, you can move on to the next step on pounds pretty quickly.

122
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:38,700
 That's why you want to define success deterministically.

123
00:14:38,700 --> 00:14:42,590
 Do that just like Codex.

124
00:14:42,590 --> 00:14:46,920
 Write the test and review it when you can.

125
00:14:46,920 --> 00:14:48,950
 Again, we've kind of seen this flow chart again.

126
00:14:48,950 --> 00:14:50,950
 This is more towards a team perspective.

127
00:14:50,950 --> 00:14:59,410
 Including tests, built-in steps, reviews between the actual team members or team agents.

128
00:14:59,410 --> 00:15:00,480
